{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nWith the threshold empirically derived (sibling story), flip the serious-tier code-review criteria from advisory-in-everything-but-name to actually able to BLOCK. Today only the two DET criteria (secret-detection, high-critical-security) can block; all 15 LLM criteria ship blocking_enabled: false at 0.95 — locked as the permissive-rollout invariant by ADR 0036 and pinned by tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py::test_code_review_only_det_security_criteria_are_hard_blocks. The field false-block risk is demonstrably near zero (0 finding-blocks in 162 changes).\n\n- CRITICAL DISTINCTION (the reviewer's catch): `blocking_enabled` lives on CRITERIA (the routing keys in criteria_routing.json: `security`, `api-compat`, `db-migrations`, `deletion-impact`, `tests`, `scope-intent`, …) — NOT on the consequence-BINARIES (`data_loss_without_recovery`, etc.), which are decide.py severity attributes that set a finding's IMPACT, not routing entries. So the flip is: turn `blocking_enabled: true` on the CRITERIA whose Pass-1 findings carry the serious (0.9) binaries.\n\n## What\n- DEFINITE MINIMAL SET (not a provisional mapping): consequence-binaries are scored per-finding by the verify pass (content-based), NOT \"owned\" by a criterion, so there is no principled binary→criterion table to write. The empirical basis for WHICH criteria are block-worthy is sibling 9f25's adjudication. Therefore this ticket flips exactly ONE criterion now: set `blocking_enabled: true` + `block_threshold` = 9f25's derived value on **`security`** (the AGENT criterion under which the #518-class importlib code-execution finding lands — a security finding). Every other LLM criterion stays advisory at 0.95; the two DET criteria (secret-detection, high-critical-security) stay blocking as-is.\n- Any EXPANSION of the blocking set beyond `security` (e.g. api-compat, db-migrations, deletion-impact, tests) is explicitly OUT OF SCOPE here and gated on 9f25's per-criterion adjudication showing those criteria's findings are block-worthy at the derived threshold — filed as a follow-up if 9f25's data supports it, NOT guessed here. (This is why #539-class correctness findings — which have no clean owning criterion in the overlay set — are not force-mapped.)\n- Update ADR 0036 (dated note: permissive rollout concluded for `security`, evidence attached) and ALL THREE blocking-set pinning tests, each updated to the new approved set `{secret-detection, high-critical-security, security}` and each still asserting NO OTHER criterion blocks: `tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py::test_code_review_only_det_security_criteria_are_hard_blocks`, `tests/unit/test_code_review_ws2.py::test_secrets_security_keys_are_the_ws5_blocking_handoff` (line 64: `assert set(blocking) == {...}`), AND `tests/unit/test_code_review_deletion_impact.py` (lines ~102/104 pin `deletion-impact` blocking_enabled is False — which stays False under this minimal set, so that test's assertion is UNCHANGED but must be confirmed to still hold).\n- Keep pass-3 separation intact: this is a threshold/posture CONFIG change only — no decide.py math changes.\n- NOTE: this depends on 9f25's derived threshold; if 9f25's honest crossover comes out ABOVE 0.54/0.60, AC4's \"#518/#539-class findings now BLOCK\" is revisited with 9f25's actual number (do not force a threshold to satisfy the AC — the epic's Definitions record this contingency).\n\n## Scope\nsrc/rebar/llm/code_review/criteria_routing.json, tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py, tests/unit/test_code_review_ws2.py + tests/unit/test_code_review_deletion_impact.py (the second and third blocking-set pinning tests), docs/adr/0036-*.md, docs/plan-review-gate.md (the cross-gate posture note), tests/unit/test_code_review_blocking_replay.py (self-contained serious-vs-NIT blocking replay). Depends on the derivation story 9f25 (consumes its derived threshold + its code-review derivation/replay script).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The `security` criterion has blocking_enabled: true at the derived block_threshold in criteria_routing.json; all other LLM criteria remain advisory at 0.95 (expansion beyond `security` is deferred to 9f25's data).\n- [ ] ALL THREE blocking-set pinning tests assert the new approved set `{secret-detection, high-critical-security, security}` and each fails on any unapproved addition: test_impact_model_versioning.py::test_code_review_only_det_security_criteria_are_hard_blocks, test_code_review_ws2.py::test_secrets_security_keys_are_the_ws5_blocking_handoff, and test_code_review_deletion_impact.py (confirm its `deletion-impact blocking_enabled is False` assertion still holds under the minimal set).\n- [ ] ADR 0036 carries a dated enablement note citing derivation ticket 9f25.\n- [ ] A SELF-CONTAINED replay proves #518-class (security) findings now BLOCK under the now-blocking `security` criterion while false-blocks stay 0 — WITHOUT depending on any sibling's not-yet-built script. Proving artifact (owned by this ticket): a unit test `tests/unit/test_code_review_blocking_replay.py` that (a) loads a small committed fixture of code_review_result_v1-shaped records — a couple of #518-class (importlib code-execution, security-criterion) findings with their real impacts, plus a set of NIT-shaped findings, and (b) applies the flipped blocking config + derived threshold via the real routing (`reg.threshold_for(...)` / the blocking decision), asserting the serious findings cross the threshold under a now-blocking criterion while the NIT set yields 0 blocks. Proving command: `.venv/bin/pytest tests/unit/test_code_review_blocking_replay.py -q`. (9f25 owns the corpus-wide adjudication + derivation; this AC only proves the config change makes qualifying findings block.) If 9f25's honest threshold cannot make these findings block without false-blocks, this AC is renegotiated against 9f25's data rather than forced.\n- [ ] make lint passes on the change.\n- [ ] make typecheck passes on the change.\n- [ ] make test passes on the change."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783891207399149001,"uuid":"cdefcd72-3a8d-48ca-a73e-9f0f25135e58"}